const e={title:"Delights",tagline:"A kanban board for the things you're looking forward to.",what:"Delights is a kanban board for the things you're looking forward to — books to read, restaurants to try, places to visit — not obligations, just things that sound fun. Each list moves items through Want to → Enjoying → Satisfied, so anticipation has somewhere to live and completion gets its own moment.",screenshot:"/help/delight/01-new-list.png",howTo:[{heading:"Create a list",body:'Click New list, name it (e.g. "Restaurants to try"), and define up to 6 custom columns of your choosing — Text, Number, or Link type (e.g. "Cuisine," "Price," "Website").',screenshot:"/help/delight/01-new-list.png"},{heading:"Add items",body:`Use Add or the + on any lane to add a card — fill in your custom columns (Anvil suggests values you've typed before, so repeat entries like "Italian" autocomplete). Put it straight in whichever lane fits.`},{heading:"Drag between lanes",body:"Move a card from Want to → Enjoying → Satisfied as you go, or reorder within a lane by priority.",screenshot:"/help/delight/02-kanban-board.png"},{heading:"Close the loop when you finish",body:'Dragging (or adding) a card into Satisfied pops up a small completion prompt: the date (defaults to today) and an optional "How was it?" note — this is what turns "crossed off" into an actual memory you can look back on.'},{heading:'Use a "tags" column to filter',body:'Name any column "tag" or "tags" and its comma-separated values automatically become filterable chips at the top of the board.'}],why:`Most productivity tools are built entirely around obligation — tasks, deadlines, things you have to do. Delights is deliberately the opposite: a dedicated place for things you want to do, tracked with the same care as everything else.

• Anticipation is a real form of well-being, and it needs a home. Research on happiness consistently finds that looking forward to something contributes as much to wellbeing as the experience itself. If your only system is a to-do list, the fun stuff never gets written down anywhere — and what doesn't get written down quietly stops happening.

• The three-lane structure ("Want to → Enjoying → Satisfied") mirrors how desire actually plays out, instead of collapsing everything into a flat checkbox. Seeing something sit in "Enjoying" — actively happening — is its own small pleasure that a plain todo-done binary erases.

• The completion note closes the loop instead of just crossing something off. "How was it?" takes two seconds to answer but turns a finished item into a small archived memory instead of a checkbox that silently disappears. Months later, that note is the difference between remembering you did something and remembering how it actually felt.

Used consistently, Delights is meant to counterbalance a life run entirely by obligation — a reminder, in the same app where you track discipline and habits, that pursuing things purely because they sound good is also worth doing on purpose.`};export{e as default};
